==Anglo-Saxon==

===Verb===
'''wífian'''

# to marry, take a wife; ''used of a man''

===Pronunciation===
*wiev·i·an, ye·wiev·i·an

Note: this verb may appear with or without the [[ge-]] prefix, without a change in meaning

===Declension===
*Class 2 Weak Transitive Verb
====Present Tense====
=====Indicative=====
*Singular: ic wífie, þu wífast, hé wífaþ
*plural: wé, gé, híe wífiaþ
=====Subjunctive=====
*Singular: wífie
*plural: wífien
=====Imperative=====
*Singular: wífa!
*plural: wífiaþ!
=====Participle=====
*wífiende
====Past Tense====
=====Indicative=====
*Singular: ic wífode, þu wífodest, hé wífode
*plural: wé, gé, híe wífodon
=====Subjunctive=====
*Singular: wífode
*plural: wífoden
=====Participle=====
*gewífod
====Inflected Infinitive====
*tó wífienne

===Etymology===
*Derived from [[wíf]] {{n}}, ''woman, wife''.

===Synonyms===
*[[Anglo-Saxon]]: [[ǽwnian]], [[beǽwnian]], [[beweddian]], [[ceorlian]] (of a woman), [[fetian]], [[geǽwnian]], [[geceorlian]] (of a woman), [[gefetian]], [[gehǽman]], [[gehíwian]], [[gewífian]] (of a man), [[mǽnsumian]], [[gémungian]], [[gesinigian]], [[geweddian]], [[hǽman]], [[híwian]], [[mǽnsumian]], [[wógian]]

===Antonyms===
*[[Anglo-Saxon]]: [[ceorlian]] (of a woman); [[tótwǽman]] to divorce
*English: to [[divorce]]